[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Hyatt Mayor's father was marine biologist Alfred Goldsborough Mayor (1868–1922) and his mother was artist and sculptor Harriet Randolph Hyatt Mayor.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] His grandfather, whose name he carried, was the paleontologist Alpheus Hyatt.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Mayor came from an artistic family; his mother's sister was the sculptor Anna Hyatt Huntington, and her husband was art patron Archer Milton Huntington, founder of the Hispanic Society of America in 1904.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Mayor received his B.A. from Princeton University (1922) and then received a Rhodes scholarship, which he used to earn his second bachelor's degree at Christ Church, Oxford in 1926.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] The next few years he spent in Florence, Italy and at the American School of Classical Studies.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Upon returning to the United States he embarked on a literary career, working on *Hound & Horn*.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] He married Virginia Sluder in 1932 and then joined the Department of Prints at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, becoming curator of the department in 1946.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] He had to follow the massive figure of William Ivins, Jr., whose curatorship had lasted 30 years.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] His tenure was marked by significant acquisitions of engravings, woodcuts, and other printed material, some by then-unknown artists who proved later to be eminently collectible.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Many European collections became available after World War II, and there were notable acquisitions, especially from the collection of the Prince of Lichtenstein.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] He also expanded which types of types of printed ephemera were considered worthy of collection to include postcards, baseball cards and advertisements.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] He accepted the Jefferson Burdick collection at the Met, which included 300,000 items of American prints and memorabilia.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] In 1952 he published *Prints and People: A Social History of Printed Pictures*, which has remained continuously in print.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] In 2016, the Metropolitan Museum of Art celebrated the centenary of the founding of its Department of Prints with *The Power of Prints: The Legacy of William M.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] The exhibit explored the breath and depth of the collection created by Ivins and Mayor.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] The exhibit was accompanied by a catalog of the same name by Freyda Spira and Peter Parshall.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Rosenbach Lectures in Bibliography in 1965.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] In 1955 he had succeeded his uncle Archer as president of the Hispanic Society of America, and he continued to serve until his death.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] He also served as a trustee of the American Federation of Arts and of Brookgreen Gardens in South Carolina.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] He was awarded a Boston Museum Award in 1971.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] Among other accolades he received, French poet St.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/a-hyatt-mayor] His granddaughter is actress Yeardley Smith.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] Shull was born in Miami County, Ohio to Harrison and Catherine Ryman Shull.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] Two of his siblings included Charles Albert Shull (1879–1962) who became a professor of plant physiology and George Harrison Shull (1874–1954) who became professor of botany and genetics.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] Another brother was the botanical illustrator James Marion Shull (1872–1948).
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He grew up on the family farm, learning first hand about agriculture and plants.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] After an informal early schooling, he received an AB from the University of Michigan in 1908 and briefly joined the Michigan Biological Survey.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He then joined Columbia University where he became interested in heredity, inspired by T.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He examined the influence of environmental factors on development.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He received a PhD in 1911 and became a zoology instructor at the University of Michigan.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He began to examine sex determination in rotifers and conducted experiments on mutation induction and crossing in *Drosophila*.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He also conducted experiments on insect biology and took a special interest in polymorphisms such as in the presence or absence of wings in aphids.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] Shull was a critical opponent of suggestions on mimetic relationships based on human visual observation.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] McAtee showed from stomach contents of birds that mimics and models were eaten in proportion to their availability.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He believed that care needed to be taken to examine the predator and their perception.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He was an evolutionist but believed that many of the contemporary researchers were too descriptive and lacking rigour in their claims.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] In his teaching he believed that there had to be specific principles including cell organization, genetics, systematics and distribution rather than merely descriptions of "type specimens".
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] He also believed that a purely historical approach to teaching biology did not help unify the field.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] Shull married zoologist Margaret Jeffrey Buckley, who was an instructor at Grinnell College in Iowa.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/aaron-franklin-shull] They had four children, including the geneticist Elizabeth Shull Russell, who later worked at the Jackson Laboratory and was elected to the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] He attended Columbia University majoring in chemistry.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] When he started graduate studies he took interest in the work of Thomas Hunt Morgan.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] Morgan took Tyler, and several other graduate students and research fellows with him, to the California Institute of Technology when he was hired to establish the new Division of Biology.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] Tyler completed his Ph.D. studies on reproductive biology and was appointed to the faculty at Caltech.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] Tyler's research looked at development and differentiation of embryos from a range of marine organisms.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] He made early use of immunohistochemical techniques and was one of the first researchers to recognize that maternal messenger RNA present in the ovum could affect differentiation.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/albert-tyler-biologist] His research on nucleic acid and protein synthesis in sea urchin eggs was cut short when he died unexpectedly in 1968.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] Alpheus Hyatt II was born in Washington, D.C. to Alpheus Hyatt and Harriet Randolph (King) Hyatt.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He briefly attended the Maryland Military Academy and Yale University, and after graduating from Harvard University in 1862, he enlisted as a private in the Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry for the Civil War, emerging with the rank of captain.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] After the war he worked for a time at the Essex Institute (now the Peabody Essex Museum in Salem, Massachusetts.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He and a colleague founded *American Naturalist* and Hyatt served as editor from 1867 to 1870.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He became a professor of paleontology and zoology at Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1870, where he taught for eighteen years, and was professor of biology and zoology at Boston University from 1877 until his death in 1902.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He also served as curator of the Boston Society of Natural History, where his longtime assistant was his former student Jennie Maria Arms Sheldon, and he established a laboratory at the Norwood-Hyatt House in 1879 for the study of Marine Biology in Annisquam, Massachusetts.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] The River Road building gave him access to the Annisquam River, a salt water estuary.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] This enterprise was moved to Woods Hole and became the Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory in 1888.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] Hyatt studied under Louis Agassiz and was a proponent of Neo-Lamarckism with Edward Drinker Cope.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] In 1869, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences elected him a fellow and in 1875, he was elected a member of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1895.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] In 1898, he received the honorary degree of LL.D. from Brown University.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He and his wife, Audella Beebe, were the parents of famed sculptor Anna Hyatt Huntington; their other children were Harriet Randolph Hyatt Mayor, who was a less well known sculptor (and mother of the art historian A.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] Hyatt's views on the evolution of species was expressed in his 1866 paper on *On the Parallelism between the Different Stages of Life in the Individual and Those in the Entire Group of the Molluscous Order Tetrabranchiata*.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] In this he claimed that extinction of a species was analogous to death of individual organisms.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] He proposed that there was an acceleration and a deceleration in the number of species over time which preceded extinction.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] The movement toward this Neo-Lamarckian understanding was supported by Edward Drinker Cope and Alpheus S.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/alpheus-hyatt] Allen, Clarence King, Joseph Le Conte, and Henry Fairfield Osborn.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] The journal was founded by Alpheus Hyatt, Edward S.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] Putnam at the Essex Institute in Salem, Massachusetts.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] The first issue appeared in print dated March 1867.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] In 1885 the four men founded the American Naturalist Society, where in 1887 the journal was designated an official organ of the society for publication.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] In 1878 the journal was for sale and Edward Cope bought half the rights.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] He moved the journal to Philadelphia and arranged to edit it jointly with Professor Alpheus S.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] Cope became editor-in-chief in 1887 and continued in that capacity until his death in 1897.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] In 1897, a group of professors from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Harvard University, and Tufts University bought the rights from the Cope estate and kept the journal in publication until 1907 when J.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] Cattell's son Jacques became co-editor and publisher with his father in 1939.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-naturalist] Although the ASN became increasingly involved in editing *The American Naturalist* through changes in 1941 and 1951, the journal remained with the Cattell family until 1968, when the University of Chicago Press took it over after Jaques Cattell's death.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-society-of-naturalists] The **American Society of Naturalists** (**ASN**) was founded in 1883 and is one of the oldest professional societies dedicated to the biological sciences in North America.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-society-of-naturalists] Founded in Massachusetts with Alpheus Spring Packard Jr. as its first president, it was called the **Society of Naturalists of the Eastern United States** until 1886.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-society-of-naturalists] The scientific journal *The American Naturalist* is published on behalf of the society.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-society-of-naturalists] The Society holds an annual meeting, commonly called 'Evolution', jointly with the Society for the Study of Evolution and Society of Systematic Biologists, with a scientific program of symposia and contributed papers and posters.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-society-of-naturalists] Wilson), the Early Career Investigators Award for promising scientists early in their careers (originally named for Jasper Loftus-Hills), among other awards.
[src:alpheus-hyatt/american-society-of-naturalists] The current president and vice-president are Daniel I.
